	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>The Spanish fleet could be forced out by Mauritania’s ban on tickler chains for shrimp trawlers </h1>

			
			<h4>
												05 July 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The Spanish Fisheries Confederation (Cepesca) has reported that the Mauritanian authorities have indicated their intention of banning the use of tickler chains by shrimp trawlers. The 26 vessels that make up the Spanish shellfish fleet that operates under the EU–Mauritania agreement would be ‘forced’ out, and would not be able to renew their licences from 1 July 2011 due to that measure.</p><p>The president of the National Association of Shipowners (ANAMAR) feels that the ban conflicts with the terms of the agreement, which, during the FPA joint committee in 2008, took the decision to continue the use of these chains until the EU–Mauritania joint scientific committee assesses their impact. According to the sector, the ban would decrease by 20% and 40% the catches of shrimp and prawn, respectively, and double the amount of discards in each set.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
Press article, <i>Europa Press</i>, ‘La flota marisquera amenaza con abandonar el caladero mauritano si el país no respeta medidas acordadas’, 17 May 2011<br />

<a href="http://www.europapress.es/economia/noticia-economia-pesca-flota-marisquera-amenaza-abandonar-caladero-mauritano-si-pais-no-respeta-medidas-acordadas-20110517184710.html" target="_self">http://www.europapress.es/economia/noticia-economia-pesca-flota-marisque...</a><br />
Press article, <i>Fish Information &amp; Services</i>, 27 May 2011<br />
<a href="http://fis.com/fis/worldnews/worldnews.asp?l=e&amp;country=0&amp;special=&amp;monthyear=&amp;day=&amp;id=43093&amp;ndb=1&amp;df=0" target="_self">http://fis.com/fis/worldnews/worldnews.asp?l=e&amp;country=0&amp;special...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Mauritania has for some years been developing a management plan for its shrimp fishery, with the support of some EU member states. Amongst the main issues identified in the plan are the high levels of by-catch; for every kg of shrimps caught, there is around 5 kg of other fish caught (much of which is discarded and dead, as the legally acceptable levels of by-catch are much lower than those actually taken). Related issues include the need to prevent over-exploitation by the local and foreign shrimp trawlers, and the need to minimise the impact of trawling on sea bottoms, particularly in sensitive areas. Banning tickler chains may have a positive impact on minimising the impact on the environment, but there are also indications that it may provoke a higher level of by-catch. This issue highlights the crucial importance of developing a dialogue through the FPA, with the objective of achieving sustainable fisheries exploitation. It would certainly be beneficial to all parties concerned to discuss such complex technical issues and find the solutions that will best promote sustainable fisheries in Mauritanian waters.</p>
		</div>
		
